event_data.Name: New York Fashion Week
event_data.Description: This was space for a visual feast of ceiling high stacked speakers, nostalgic sing-alongs accompanied by original artwork, walls of decadence dripping in gold, and chill vibes after a day of runways.

exhibit_data.title: Moses Sumney and Kelela
exhibit_data.Description: A live collaborative musical performance featuring Moses Sumney and Saint Heron artist, Kelela. Conjoining forces, these genre-defying performers form an organic development between Sumney’s "one man soul orchestra" and the rich vocal layers of Kelela. Utilizing the apparatus of his voice, Sumney looped vocals to create melodies, beats and lyrics to form poetic and soulful textures, while Kelela’s alluring sound heightened the listening experience. The performance was framed on either end with compelling sets by DJ Lindsey and DJ Kitty Cash.

exhibit_data.title: Music Video Karaoke
exhibit_data.Description: Revitalizing an endeared musical relic, these vibrant visual artists took over the backdrops of a video karaoke machine. Attendees got a chance to perform their favorite R&B songs in front of these moving artworks and share them with their social media networks in realtime.
exhibit_data.Exhibitor: Terence Nance and Hisham Akira Bharoocha

exhibit_data.title: Go For Gold
exhibit_data.Description: Combining the juxtaposed elements of gold chains and stacked speakers, the space spoke directly to the opulence and urban edge of R&B. Draped in glistening gold chains, the room was a gilded hall: each surface glittering and decadent to the touch. Looming large, the stacked speakers reference the rocksteady Jamaican dancehall vibes. It all came to life as lights hit the glittering surfaces and the music started.

event_data.Name: Sundance Film Festival
event_data.Description: This was space for confetti walls, dixie marching bands, meticulous line work, moving vocals, piñata breaking and portraits of auras.

exhibit_data.title: My Brightest Diamond
exhibit_data.Description: This musical performance literally marched down Main Street and drew the crowd inside for an intimate performance. The band My Brightest Diamond mixes classical styles from opera and chamber music with rock, and now marching bands. Lead singer Shara Worden was joined by a dixie marching band that made a path into the venue.

exhibit_data.title: DM Stith
exhibit_data.Description: DM Stith is a solo musical artist who has also performed alongside Sufjan Stevens and My Brightest Diamond. His work involves guitar, layered voices and moving vocals. For this performance he played songs off of his long-awaited upcoming album.

exhibit_data.title: Mac DeMarco
exhibit_data.Description: Canadian-born musician Mac DeMarco is known for getting wonderfully strange as he rocks out on a guitar he bought for $30 when he was 16. For this show he performed some new tracks ahead of his recently announced national tour as well as had his girlfriend climb on his shoulders and smash a piñata.

exhibit_data.title: Complex Fringe Wall/Crystal Piñata/Tassel Garland
exhibit_data.Description: CONFETTISYSTEM transforms simple materials into interactive objects that create a point of focus, where memories are made and a spontaneous collaboration with the viewer is sparked. For this space, CONFETTISYSTEM created an immersive environment inspired by their love/exploration of celebration. The work also served as an interactive performance space culminating in a piñata party.

exhibit_data.title: Churn
exhibit_data.Description: Musician / visual artist / designer Hisham Bharoocha uses detailed line work and bold geometric shapes to visualize his interest in the architecture of the mind. The line work represents the experiences, thoughts, and feelings that churn in our minds constantly while the bold geometric forms imply a balance that can be found within the chaotic mind.

exhibit_data.title: The Portrait Machine Project
exhibit_data.Description: Van de Roer exhibited and made portraits of familiar personalities from the Sundance Film Festival community using a Polaroid aura camera. He asks where in the relationship between artist, camera, subject and viewer does authorship of a portrait lie and what insight do we expect from a portrait of someone familiar.

event_data.Name: Art Week Miami
event_data.Description: This was space for music, partying sheep, old record players, emotional balloons, documentary-filming robots, murals and French DJs at one of the biggest art events in the world.

exhibit_data.title: Gesaffelstein
exhibit_data.Description: Mike Levy, aka Gesaffelstein, the French techno artist and DJ who's remixed Justice, Depeche Mode, and Lana Del Ray, among others, and produced two tracks ("Black Skinhead" and \"Send It Up\") on Kanye West's Yeezus, performed in front of a gold mural which was inspired by his debut album Aleph and commissioned specifically for this Miami performance.

exhibit_data.title: Jacques Greene
exhibit_data.Description: As part of the night's set, 22-year old Montreal house producer Jacques Greene—who's released a pair of well-regarded EPs and done official remixes for the likes of Radiohead, Kelly Rowland, Donna Summer, Autre Ne Veut, and Ciara, along with collaborations with How to Dress Well and Katy B—played new material he'd worked on throughout the fall.

exhibit_data.title: All Ewe Can Eat
exhibit_data.Description: The must-attend party of the year, for sheep. Anybody who's anybody who's a sheep was there. We pulled out all the stops for our party sheeple, with this one-night-only luxu-tainment experience, featuring the ballerest amenities in Miami, clean water, and all-ewe-can-eat grass. Humans were also invited. No wolves.

exhibit_data.title: Emotional Arcade
exhibit_data.Description: Are you an "emotional person?" Using specially modified EEG headsets, people played a new kind of technologically-enabled game where uncontrollable emotional expression is a strength. The only way to win is to feel. There are no losers in an Emotional Arcade game, just revelations.

exhibit_data.title: The 78 Project
exhibit_data.Description: Inspired by the field recordings of legendary song catcher Alan Lomax, "The 78 Project" is on a mission to record today's musicians with yesterday's technology. With just one microphone, an authentic 1930s PRESTO direct-to-disc recorder, and a blank lacquer disc, musicians are given the opportunity to cut a record anywhere they choose, finding in that adventure a new connection to our cultural legacy. This evening's recording featured Jubal's Kin.
exhibit_data.Exhibitor: Alex Steyermark and Lavinia Jones Wright Featuring Jubal's Kin

exhibit_data.title: BlabDroids
exhibit_data.Description: BlabDroids are making the world’s first documentary shot entirely by robots. BlabDroids are traveling the globe asking people important questions and astounding patterns are being revealed. It's true, humans can have meaningful interactions with machines, and perhaps that can be a beautiful thing after all.
